		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top">You know whats awesome about BST?<br clear=all>
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Tue, Aug 21st 11:04 AM2001 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a href="/db/classes.html?class=15&mid=9984062658293&post=1"><a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=15&mid=9984062658293&num=1&post=1&replyto=9984062658293"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=9984062658293></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <span id=>Anonymous</span></a><b><span id=></span></b>
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Anonymous&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>It was stated, oh so long ago, and I don't remember where, but it WAS stated by someone at verant that BST pets will be able to zone with the person.&nbsp;&nbsp;Maybe they were saying thats what they're going for.  You may be thinking, why would that be needed if the mana cost is 0 to summon a pet... well, simple... the buff.  You want to preserve the buff(s) on your pet to save mana.  And this brings another thought to my mind... will the "pet buffs", the ones to increase level, wear off?  Or will they last as long as the pet?  <br><br>Another reason you might be able to zone with your pet is: Maybe it IS that you have to summon an animan or other type of creature from the zone.  There are a LOT of zones where you cannot find animals or other types of mobs, so you have to go out and get one and zone back in.  I really don't think Verant would do this though.<br><br>PERSONALLY, I think that the pet will actually be SUMMONED, like every other class summons pets... not called.  Why?  The main reasons: 1) The level of the pet when it is "called".  Say you're level 10 and you "call" a level 10 - 11 pet..  well then theres no need to have the pet buff.  Also there is the matter of  there being no low level mobs in zone (refer to 3))  No... I think you're gonna conjure a basic level 1 pet (possibly with a random look) then will have to buff it to your level.  2) The lack of animals and other mobs in MANY zones across norath.  and finally 3) IF you did summon a mob from the zone... what would happen in ToV, where my level 58 druid zones in and everything on track is RED, meaning 61+?  If you had to summon a creature from the zone, in many cases the creature's level woud actually have to be LOWERED, probably to 1, in order for it to be an acceptable pet, and then you would have to buff it to an acceptable level.  And what about the loot on that pet?  What happens to it?  What if theres 1 bear with a HQ pelt or 1 lion with a HQ pelt running through the zone and you cast your spell and the bear / lion comes to you and becomes your pet?  No one gets the pelt.  Same is true in other zones.  Yet another point... Even if they made it by level cap.. at level 60, a blue pet would be able to hit for over 100, whereas most other pet classes don't even get pets that hit for close to 100.<br><br>Anyway.. just my 2cp.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >1 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
		   <table class="mform2"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Tue, Aug 21st 1:33 PM2001 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=15&mid=9984062658293&num=1&post=1&replyto=99841518315334"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=99841518315334></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=16816"><span id=>guldur</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>2 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.50]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=guldur&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>The above is suppose to be for all pet classes.<br>Here is the ASK BRAD article talking about it.<br><br>Hi Brad,<br><br>I've been playing EverQuest for a limited amount of time now, and there's one thing which boggled my mind pretty much from the first time my poor necro managed to summon a pet, and then loose it cos he walked across a zone boundary.<br><br>Why DO pets vanish at the boundary? Is it a balance issue, or are/were there technical reasons.<br><br>Both technical and balance issues, really. It is more difficult to pass an NPC (which pets are) from one zone to another, but it is possible (for example, boats are really NPCs, and they move zone to zone). But we also wanted character classes with pets to have to summon pets every once in a while instead of them being persistent - it allows for different types of pets to be summoned and with some variation of their attributes, etc. So in that it was difficult to have them zone in the first place, it sort of made sense to use that as one of the mechanisms by which the player would need to summon another pet.<br><br>All that said, it looks like we might have 'familiars' in Luclin, which are really persistent pets that would indeed stay with you when you zone. <br><br>This, of course, leads to a second question: Why do mobs stop at a zone boundary. Again, is it for technical reasons, or was it intended for the players to be able to run to safety by moving into a neighboring zone?<br><br>Again, both. By making zones more self-contained it was and is easier to balance them. Knowing that NPCs stop at zones allows us to put the world together with a more modular approach. And, as I said earlier, it is more difficult to have NPCs zone, although they can (for example, I heard recently that after a very powerful dragon was unleashed it traveled to several zones, slaying its enemies all over the face of Norrath). <br></p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td class=mhback align=right><span class=mh id=fs8><a class=mh href=/db/classes.html?class=15><img src=/shared/root_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Up" width=17 height=11> Thread Index</a> |  <a class=mh href=/db/classes.html?class=15&post=1><img src=/shared/new_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="New" width=17 height=11> New Subject</a> | <a class=mh href=/db/classes.html?class=15&mid=9984062658293&num=1&post=1&mid=9984062658293><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply" width=17 height=11> Reply to Thread</a></span></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="mform"><tr><td id="fs8">1 Post [ <a href="/fsearch.html?base=class15">Search Forums</a> ]</nobr></td></tr></table>&nbsp;</td></tr>
